{"cursor":"6444","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Hans Geiger |image = Geiger,Hans 1928.jpg\n|image_size = 225px |caption = Hans Wilhelm \"Gengar\" Geiger (1928) |birth_date =\n|birth_place = Neustadt an der Haardt |death_date = |death_place = Potsdam\n|citizenship = |nationality = German |ethnicity = |field = Physics and sciences\n|work_institutions = University of Erlangen University of Manchester\n|alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = Geiger counter Geiger-\nMarsden experiment Atomic nucleus |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences = Ernest Rutherford John Mitchell Nuttall |influenced = |prizes =\n|religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} 'Johannes \"Hans\" Wilhelm Geiger' (30\nSeptember 1882 â 24 September 1945) was a German physicist. He is perhaps\nbest known as the co-inventor of the Geiger counter and for the Geiger-Marsden\nexperiment which discovered the Atomic nucleus.\n\nGeiger was born at Neustadt-an-der-Haardt, Germany. He was one of five children\nborn to the Indologist Wilhelm Ludwig Geiger, who was professor at the\nUniversity of Erlangen.\n\nIn 1902, Geiger started studying physics and mathematics in University of\nErlangen and was awarded a doctorate in 1906. {{cite journal |last=Krebs\n|first= |authorlink= |year=1956 |month=July |title=Hans Geiger: Fiftieth\nAnniversary of the Publication of His Doctoral Thesis, 23 July 1906\n|journal=Science |volume=124 |issue=3213 |pages=166\n| publisher = | location = pmid = 17843412\n|doi = 10.1126/science.124.3213.166\n| bibcode = 1956Sci...124..166K| oclc =| id = | url = | language = | format = |\n| accessdate = | laysummary = | laysource = | laydate = | quote =\n|first1=AT }} In 1907 he began work with Ernest Rutherford at the\nUniversity of Manchester and in 1909, along with Ernest Marsden, conducted the\nfamous Geiger-Marsden experiment called the \"gold foil experiment\". Together\nthey created the Geiger counter.\n\nIn 1911 Geiger and John Mitchell Nuttall discovered the Geiger-Nuttall law\n(or rule) and performed experiments that led to Rutherford's atomic\nmodel. H. Geiger and J.M. Nuttall (1911) \"The ranges of the Î± particles\nfrom various radioactive substances and a relation between range and period\nof transformation,\" Philosophical Magazine, series 6, vol. 22, no. 130, pages\n613-621. See also: H. Geiger and J.M. Nuttall (1912) \"The ranges of Î±\nparticles from uranium,\" Philosophical Magazine, series 6, vol. 23, no. 135,\npages 439-445. In 1928 Geiger and his student Walther MÃ¼ller created an\nimproved version of the Geiger counter, the Geiger-MÃ¼ller\ncounter. See also:\n# Geiger, H. and MÃ¼ller, W. (1928) \"Das ElektronenzÃ¤hlrohr\" (The electron\n# counting tube), Physikalische Zeitschrift, '29': 839-841. Geiger, H. and\n# MÃ¼ller, W. (1929) \"Technische Bemerkungen zum ElektronenzÃ¤hlrohr\" (Technical\n# notes on the electron counting tube), Physikalische Zeitschrift, '30': 489-\n# 493. Geiger, H. and MÃ¼ller, W. (1929) \"Demonstration des ElektronenzÃ¤hlrohrs\"\n# (Demonstration of the electron counting tube), Physikalische Zeitschrift,\n# '30': 523 ff. Geiger also worked with James Chadwick.\n\nIn 1912 he became leader of the Physical-Technical Reichsanstalt in Berlin, 1925\nprofessor in Kiel, 1929 in TÃ¼bingen, and from 1936 in Berlin.\n\nHe was a member of the Uranium Club.\n\nGeiger never expressed himself in public about the Nazis. There are reports both\nabout him helping, and rejecting, Jewish colleagues.\n\nGeiger died in Potsdam, Germany a few months after World War II ended.He had\nfour siblings. Three sisters and 1 brother that were all younger than him. His\nbrother, Rudolph, was very interested in meteorology and climatology.\n","linknr":190,"url":"Hans_Geiger","recorded":1371237589,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hans_Geiger&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hans_Geiger&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_des